Built environment and mortality risk from cardiovascular disease and diabetes in Medellin, Colombia: an ecological study

Econometric analysis of the corrected manuscript submitted to Landscape and Urban Planning journal

Jorge E. Patiño, Andy Hong, Juan C. Duque, Kazem Rahimi, Silvana Zapata, and Verónica Lopera

01 April, 2021

Quantitative analysis of the relationships between built-environment features and public health outcomes in Medellin, Colombia, at the neighborhood (barrio) level. International collaboration between the Oxford Martin School at Oxford University (UK), RiSE Group at EAFIT University (CO), and the Medellin’s Health Office (CO).

Acknowledgements:
This work was completed with support from the PEAK Urban Programme, supported by 501 UKRI’s Global Challenge Research Fund, Grant Ref.: ES/P011055/1. Additionally, Kazem Rahimi is in receipt of grants from the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) Oxford Biomedical Research Centre (BRC), the Oxford Martin School (OMS), University of Oxford and the British Heart Foundation grant ref: PG/18/65/33872. The views expressed are those of the authors and not necessarily those of the OMS, the UK National Health Service (NHS), the NIHR or the Department of Health and Social Care. The funding organizations had no role in design or conduct of the study; collection, management, analysis, and interpretation of the data; preparation, review, or approval of the manuscript; or decision to submit the manuscript for publication.

Spatial dependence tests

Create contiguity matrices

# build contiguity matrix
Wr = poly2nb(as_Spatial(dataset), queen = FALSE) # Rook matrix
Wq = poly2nb(as_Spatial(dataset), queen = TRUE) # Queen matrix
# convert matrix to lists
listWr = nb2listw(Wr, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)
listWq = nb2listw(Wq, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)
# inverse distance matrix
mycoords <- coordinates(as_Spatial(dataset))
mydm <- rdist(mycoords)                  # computes distance in projected coordinates
for(i in 1:dim(mydm)[1]) {mydm[i,i] = 0} # renders exactly zero all diagonal elements
mydm[mydm > 1000] <- 0                   # all distances > 1000 miles are set to zero
mydm <- ifelse(mydm!=0, 1/mydm, mydm)    # inverting distances
listWid <- mat2listw(mydm, style="W")    # create a (normalized) listw object

Lagrange Multiplier (LM) tests

Test run on OLS models using three different contiguity matrix specifications:
- Rook: listWr.
- Queen: listWq.
- Inverse distance: listWid.

DCS
